  "prompt": "What are the laws regarding multiple wage garnishments in the state of Arkansas?",
  "response": "In Arkansas, there are specific laws governing wage garnishments:\n\n1. Maximum Garnishment Limits:\n- Federal law limits garnishment to 25% of disposable earnings or the amount by which weekly earnings exceed 30 times the federal minimum wage, whichever is less.\n\n2. Priority of Garnishments:\n- Multiple garnishments are typically processed in the order they are received.\n- Certain types of garnishments (like child support) may take precedence.\n\n3. Protections:\n- Arkansas has some of the most protective wage garnishment laws in the United States.\n- Certain types of income (Social Security, disability, etc.) are generally exempt from garnishment.\n\n4. Restrictions:\n- An employer cannot fire an employee due to a single wage garnishment.\n- However, multiple garnishments might complicate employment status.\n\n5. Consumer Debt:\n- For most consumer debts, only one garnishment is typically allowed at a time.\n\n6. Specific Exceptions:\n- Tax debts, child support, and federal student loans may have different garnishment rules.\n\nFor the most current and specific details, it's recommended to consult with an Arkansas employment law attorney or the Arkansas Department of Labor.",
